│ This is a tricky bug. The core issue is that the `nofpclass` │
│ attribute doesn't constrain the sign of a NaN, but the       │
│ optimizer was incorrectly assuming it did. My previous       │
│ attempts failed because they were either too aggressive,     │
│ causing regressions, or too complex and still incorrect.     │
│                                                              │
│ The root cause analysis correctly identified the problem:    │
│ the optimization transforms `copysign(x, y)` to `copysign(x, │
│ -1.0)` (or `copysign(x, +1.0)`) without considering that `x` │
│ could be a NaN, whose sign should be determined by `y`, not  │
│ forced.                                                      │
│                                                              │
│ The correct fix is to ensure this optimization only applies  │
│ when we can prove the result will not be a NaN. There are    │
│ two ways to prove this:                                      │
│ 1. The `copysign` instruction itself has a `nnan` (no-nan)   │
│ flag.                                                        │
│ 2. The `nofpclass` attribute on the function return value    │
│ explicitly forbids NaNs (i.e., `nofpclass(nan)` is present). │
│ This information is captured in the `DemandedMask`.          │
│                                                              │
│ I will implement a fix that checks for either of these       │
│ conditions before applying the sign-forcing optimization.    │
│                                                              │
│ First, I will reset the file to its original state.          │
│ <tool_call>                                                  │
│ {                                                            │
│   "name": "reset",                                           │
│   "args": {                                                  │
│     "file":                                                  │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSimplifyDemanded │
│ .cpp"                                                        │
│   }                                                          │
│ }                                                            │
│ </tool_call>                                                 │
│ Now I will apply the correct, minimal patch.                 │
│ <tool_call>                                                  │
│ {                                                            │
│   "name": "edit",                                            │
│   "args": {                                                  │
│     "file":                                                  │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSimplifyDemanded │
│ .cpp",                                                       │
│     "old": "      if ((DemandedMask & fcPositive) == fcNone) │
│ {\n        // Roundabout way of replacing with fneg(fabs)\n  │
│ I->setOperand(1, ConstantFP::get(VTy, -1.0));\n              │
│ return I;\n      }\n\n      if ((DemandedMask & fcNegative)  │
│ == fcNone) {\n        // Roundabout way of replacing with    │
│ fabs\n        I->setOperand(1, ConstantFP::getZero(VTy));\n  │
│ return I;\n      }",                                         │
│     "new": "      // If we can't return a positive value, we │
│ must be returning a negative\n      // value. This is not    │
│ true for NaNs, which can have a positive sign bit\n      //  │
│ but are not in fcPositive. The transform is safe if we know  │
│ the\n      // result is not a NaN.\n      if ((DemandedMask  │
│ & fcPositive) == fcNone) {\n        if (I->hasNoNaNs() ||    │
│ (DemandedMask & fcNan) == fcNone) {\n          // Roundabout │
│ way of replacing with fneg(fabs)\n          I->setOperand(1, │
│ ConstantFP::get(VTy, -1.0));\n          return I;\n          │
│ }\n      }\n\n      // If we can't return a negative value,  │
│ we must be returning a positive\n      // value. This is not │
│ true for NaNs. The transform is safe if we know the\n        │
│ // result is not a NaN.\n      if ((DemandedMask &           │
│ fcNegative) == fcNone) {\n        if (I->hasNoNaNs() ||      │
│ (DemandedMask & fcNan) == fcNone) {\n          // Roundabout │
│ way of replacing with fabs\n          I->setOperand(1,       │
│ ConstantFP::getZero(VTy));\n          return I;\n        }\n │
│ }"                                                           │
│   }                                                          │
│ }                                                            │
│ </tool_call>                                                 │
│ The patch has been applied. Now, I will verify it with the   │
│ test suite.                                                  │
